  "answer": "The critic’s objections fail because each forbidden case is a concrete, realistically possible observation that would directly test the target’s mechanism, and the critic misreads both the scope and the logic of the cases. (1) The first case is concrete and realistic: the target’s scope covers Mycenaean Greece, and Crete was part of the Mycenaean administrative sphere using Linear B; discovering post‑1150 BC Linear B tablets demonstrating continued palace administration would directly contradict the claimed abrupt phase transition and is an entirely plausible archaeological find, given the incompleteness of the Linear B corpus. (2) The second case is also concrete and realistic: Ugarit’s destruction ca. 1190 BC does not preclude a prior administrative reversion to cuneiform-only record‑keeping within the decades before destruction; such a reversion is a specific, observable archaeological pattern (e.g., a stratum with only cuneiform administrative texts above one with alphabetic texts) that would directly test whether loss of alphabetic administrative writing preceded collapse. (3) The third case is not invalidated by Egypt’s exclusion from the scope; the case posits evidence from Egypt of a scribal‑monopoly crisis without systemic collapse, which would serve as a crucial comparative test of the mechanism’s necessity — if the same information‑structure crisis occurred in a polity explicitly excluded from the claim’s scope and did not produce collapse, that would undermine the mechanism’s explanatory power, making it a legitimate, concrete forbidden observation."
